WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
6 new English from BBCLearningEnglish.com

2
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6 minute English from BBCLearningEnglish, I'm Pippa.

3
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
And I'm Phil, what was your favourite game when you were a child, Pippa?

4
00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:21.000
I think my favourite game was skipping with a skipping rope. How about you?

5
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Well, I could never skip, so I think I just prefer playing football.

6
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Ah, well, that's a good game to play in the playground.

7
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:34.000
80 years ago, it was quite common for children in Britain's cities to play in bomb sites.

8
00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.000
The ruins of houses which have been destroyed in World War II.

9
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Today, the idea is back in fashion, with kids playing not in bomb sites, but in junk playgrounds.

10
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Also called Adventure playgrounds.

11
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:52.000
In contrast to pre-made playgrounds where swings and slides are fixed in place,

12
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.000
Adventure playgrounds provide pieces of building materials for kids to build things themselves.

13
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:06.000
Reporter William Kramer went to see one such playground in Recsum, North Wales, for BBC World Service program, people fixing the world.

14
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
At first glance, the land is little more than a junkyard.

15
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:14.000
There are stacks of used wooden pallets and big reels for holding wires.

16
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:20.000
But if you look a little bit closer, you'll see crooked homemade structures, Heidi holes and turrets.

17
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:26.000
Children run barefoot, they swing on ropes and throw themselves down and make shift water slide.

18
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
At first glance, William sees only junk.

19
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:35.000
The phrase at first glance means looking at something for the first time before having a chance to look more carefully.

20
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Adventure playgrounds are indeed full of junk, pieces of construction material like old tires,

21
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
planks of wood and lengths of rope.

22
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:52.000
But look closely, and you'll see children using the junk to play, building dens and Heidi holes.

23
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:58.000
A Heidi hole is a small place for hiding things, or in this case, for children to hide themselves.

24
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:04.000
In this episode, we'll be hearing how Adventure playgrounds are giving kids the freedom and space to play.

25
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:15.000
As usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases, and remember, you can find all this episodes for a capillary along with a transcript on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com.

26
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
But now I have a question for you, Pipper.

27
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:30.000
We know that Adventure playgrounds started off after the Second World War, but in which country was it a, France, B, Germany, or C, Denmark?

28
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Hmm, I think maybe France, I think French children maybe were very adventurous.

29
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
Okay, but we'll find out the answer that question later in the program.

30
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Adventure playgrounds give kids the freedom to choose how they play.

31
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:56.000
According to child development expert, Dr. Anna Housley, just a, this freedom is vital, as she explains here to BBC World Services people fixing the world.

32
00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:07.000
It's true. We do pretend to minimize play in certain ways, but actually, after the most basic needs are met for children, so food, shelter, water, safe place to be.

33
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:12.000
Play is by far the most important factor for healthy child development.

34
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:21.000
Anna Housley is as important as a child's basic needs like food and safety, but unfortunately, the importance of play tends to be minimised.

35
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:26.000
If something tends to happen, it happens often, and is likely to happen again.

36
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Anna says that after a child's basic needs are met, plays by far the most important factor in a healthy childhood.

37
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:39.000
She uses the phrase by far to mean by a greater amount.

38
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
For example, your teacher might say, you're by far the best student in class.

39
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:50.000
The freedom to take controlled risks in a safe environment is what Anna calls self-directed play.

40
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Here she explains more to Myra and Neuby, presenter of BBC program People Fixing the World.

41
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:05.000
So what you're seeing is letting kids play, replay, actually, or play on their own, and kind of come up with the ideas that's really crucial for their development.

42
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.000
It's a 100% crucial for their development.

43
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:17.000
What I meant when I said that it's protective is that kids build resiliency, confidence, coping strategies, regulations, strategies.

44
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:23.000
So many of the skills that we know lead to healthy human development are developed in play.

45
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
Myra mentions the importance of free play.

46
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Anna says it's 100% crucial, meaning completely.

47
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:38.000
You can also say 100% as an informal response to mean, yes, I agree with you completely.

48
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:48.000
Adventure playgrounds have lots of small dangers, hard pieces of wood, sharp metal, nails, according to Anna, taking small risks when playing with these,

49
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.000
makes kids more resilient and builds coping strategies.

50
00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:56.000
A term for the psychological ways children develop to manage challenging situations.

51
00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.000
And Phil, I think it's time for the answer to your quiz question.

52
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
Yes, I asked you in which country adventure playground started.

53
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
You said France, but I'm afraid the correct answer was Denmark.

54
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:13.000
They were introduced by Danish architect Carl Theodore Sourenson.

55
00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned.

56
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Starting with the phrase at first glance, when you see something quickly, without a chance to consider it more carefully.

57
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
A hide-e-hole is a small place for hiding things in, or hiding yourself in.

58
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:35.000
If people tend to do something, they do it often, and will probably continue to do it in the future.

59
00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
The phrase by far means by a greater amount.

60
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Saying 100% means completely, and can be used to emphasize a statement or show that you totally agree with it.

61
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And finally, coping strategies are psychological ways of managing your emotions in challenging situations.

62
00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:01.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, but remember, you can find many more trending topics, plus a quiz, and worksheet for this episode on our website.

63
00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:06.000
BBCLanyEnglish.com. Hope to see you there soon, but for now it's goodbye.

64
00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Goodbye.
